    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The \"clutter\" you're noticing in the VP tree is a very common issue when you start adding too many modifiers, and it often signals a potential ambiguity or a need to rethink the structure. It's less about a hard-and-fast rule for when it gets \"too complex,\" and more about how you are trying to categorize the relationship between the elements.\n\nWhen a tree gets overwhelmingly dense, it's often because you are trying to cram multiple, unrelated types of modification onto one single node, which violates principles of structural clarity. A good parser, or a well-drawn tree, should ideally keep related elements grouped together in a clean hierarchy.\n\nIf you keep adding modifiers and the VP node starts looking like a tangled mess, try splitting the VP into smaller, more manageable constituents, or consider if some of those modifiers should actually be attached higher up the tree, perhaps even to the main clause structure, rather than directly to the verb.\n\nThis complexity is a real challenge in parsing, and sometimes the most elegant solution is the simplest one—don't let one node become a giant, multi-purpose hub for every piece of information! Keep simplifying the branches until the relationships are crystal clear.\n\nIt's",
      "source": "target",
